segments.text: About 9 or 10 o'clock in the evening and a cold front started coming through with the accompanying thunderstorm and it started raining and storming and we just knew we weren't going to be able to catch a ride or worse that we would catch a ride that would let us out at Hempstead or Navasota or someplace like that and we'd get soaked.
So about midnight
this big black Cadillac pulls up and stops and we look and it's a black fella and Walter and I look at each other and we've got to get out of this rain.
So we said, yes sir, where are you going?
He said, you're going to A&M, aren't you?
We said, yes we are.
He said, jump in.
So no questions, we didn't ask a question, we jumped in and
We talked on the way up, and we found out that he was a graduate student at Prairie View.
And we talked about that, and we passed Hempstead, and we passed Waller, and we passed Hempstead.
And we looked at each other, because that's where Prairie View is.
And we said, weren't you going to let us out there at Prairie View?
He says, no.
Y'all going to College Station?
I'm going to tell you to College Station.
So he drove us right up to Hart Hall and let us out.
And we said, well, we sure do thank you.
You know, we shook hands.
He says, that's okay.
He says, us Aggies got to stick together.
Oh, that's good.
That's good.
That's good.
Did you or anyone else you knew well ever have a negative hitchhiking experience?
Or something?
No, I don't recall.
I've never heard of any.
I don't recall of one.
Back to, we didn't finish on describing the student body.
Where geographically in Texas, where did they come from?
Small towns or big cities or what?
Mostly, I would say the small towns.
Particularly rural towns, agrarian.
towns and although Houston, San Antonio, Dallas, Fort Worth, and Beaumont, Beaumont is a big Aggie town, they send a lot of students up here.
My guess is that it would be 50% those five or six big towns that I mentioned and the rest small towns or no towns.
What was the key for an Aggie student to be accepted by other Aggies?
That he didn't take himself too seriously, that he had a sense of humor, that he could laugh at himself, that he had some good bull stories.
Was he expected to participate like everybody else?
Oh, absolutely.
Actually, we didn't expect.
anything like that.
It just happened.
It evolved.
But the person who did not avail himself of the benefit of the group stood out like a sore thumb.
And on rare occasions, a two percenter would find his bags back sitting outside his dorm door.
And I saw it happen.
Really?
Oh, yes.
Did some of them, did they leave or did they read the handwriting on the wall and change their attitude?
You'd try to get them to change their attitude before it ever got to that point.
That was the last resort.
And I don't know of any, I knew of very few this occurred to, but I don't know of any that didn't take the hint and leave.
Silver Taps.
Do you remember going to Silver Taps your first time?
I do.
I do.
Do you remember?
It was the strangest, saddest thing.
It didn't happen very often because we were only 6,000, 6,500 students.
But it would happen maybe once, twice a semester at the most.
Did everybody take it seriously?
Very seriously.
And all the buildings around
the inner circle around Sully's statue and the flagpole and the academic building.
It went totally dark.
All right, after you all were married, did you go to some silver taps?
Yes, we did.
Did you ever lose a dear, a close friend while you were?
No, I never had that experience.
I knew of people who did, but we never had that experience.
There were no on-campus tragedies during your four years, were there?
I don't remember having heard of any.
No.
No bus crashes and anything like that?
No.
The worst thing that happened on campus was when we had the terrible cold spell when we registered for classes on the 30th of January, 1949, the temperature dropped
to seven degrees below zero here.
Six inches of snow on the ground, we were standing in it to register as a piece of mess hall.
The OWL, which was the Southern Pacific Train from Houston to Dallas, came through to let people off at the train station, and a brake line froze, condensation in the brake line,
and the train could not move.
Now, we thought that was good bull, but to Southern Pacific, it was a tragedy because that train was sitting on the main line.
And I guess they just rerouted trains all over the place.
But it was a day and a half before they could get that train out here.
Now, how often did Aggies ride the train?
Very seldom.
I did.
once or twice as a last resort, because I couldn't get a ride out of Houston.
And we'd catch a city bus down to Houston, catch the train, I think, for two bucks, maybe two and a half.
Was there a Greyhound bus service then, here?
There was, I guess there was, but
I don't recall anybody ever writing it.
I've never heard anybody talk about writing it.
I never thought of it.
Let's see.
Muster.
Do you remember going to Muster when you were a student?
Yes.
Where was it held?
I went the first year.
Muster was held in Guyon Hall, as I recall.
Do you remember the routine?
Did they call the Muster and light candles?
No, the candle services.
had not come about until Jack Fritz and his wife perfected that in about in the 60s, I think.
But they did call, and pretty well did the student body go?
The student body went.
And then we held it out in Kyle Field when it got too big for guns.
Was there a special speaker at Muster on campus in those days?
Always.
Always.
A dignitary of some repute.
Not necessarily of academic repute.
Political types, former students,
corporate presidents who had done well, that kind of thing.
What did, for you at that time, what did Muster, what impression did it make on you?
What was its importance?
Well, the first year, Muster was new to me and I didn't understand what it was all about.
And while I was here on campus, it didn't make that much of an impression on me until many years later in life.
I became a religious muster dog.

See, one of the things that the former student association has done this year that I think is a grievous blunder, they have been paying the actual travel cost of the muster speakers like when I went to Austin.
They paid my mileage.
Oh, sure.
They've cut that out.
It will save them a total of $12,000 out of a $6 million budget.

And every muster I've ever, I've done 26 of them, every muster I've ever done, I have the impression that the key thing that audience wanted to hear the muster speaker talk about, what's happening on campus today?
What's going on?
What's important?
Like in the last two years, what about bonfire?
And what this is going to do is it's going to diminish the number of people that will go from here to other places because they'll say, hey, if I got to pay out of my pocket, I may not do it.
Like I'm going to El Paso, and we've got two grandkids out there.
And so, OK, I'll do that.
But last year, I did Charleston, South Carolina.
Year before that, Nashville.
Year before that, Colorado Springs.
Year before that, Austin.
And I think that's not good economy on their part.
Do you mean that they'd cut it out for even going to Charleston, South Carolina?
Yep.
Yep.
No longer will they pay travel expenses.
Well, at the Capital City A&M Club, when I was president and on the board for years thereafter, we always paid out of club funds.
Mm-hmm.
Now, there are some clubs that are not big enough to do that.
That's right.
And so the former students never reimbursed us.
No, no, I agree.
And then y'all were responsible for putting the person up for the night.
That's right.
And which is easy.
And their meals.
But like in Charleston, they only had about 60 people there.
And so they wouldn't have a budget.
That's hard for a little club.
Yeah, and they couldn't do it.
Like when I went to Nashville,
they were, hey, most of us haven't been to College Station in a good while.
Tell us about it.
And then what I love to tell, I ask them, how are y'all doing up here?
How is it?
And they said, it's great.
We can now get Shiner beer and Blue Bell ice cream in Nashville.
Well, I'm going to have to speak severely to Porter Garner.
Somebody, I think, made a
made a goofy decision that that's not good economy.
I like to think that I have Porter's ear because he consults with me.
Oh, good, good, good.
From time to time, not that frequently, but.
All right, let me go back.
Student indulgences.
They drank beer and whiskey.
What were people smoking then?
Were Aggies smoking?
Oh, yeah.
What were they smoking?
They were smoking Lucky Strikes, Camels, and Chesterfields.
Did Aggie smoke cigars much?
Sophomores did at Yale practice, so they could blow the smoke in the freshman's face.
And there wasn't that much cigar or pipe smoking going on.
Cigarettes, yes.
And chewing tobacco or snuff?
I'm the only guy that I know of in my end of Hart Hall that chewed tobacco.
And I'd make my roommate sick.
I'd pull that big GI can in there and I'd spit it in the can.
But chewing tobacco was not a big thing unless you were a baseball player.
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Now, and you all had never heard of the drugs, marijuana and heroin and all that?
No, we didn't know what it was.
That's what I, all right.
To us, aspirin was a drug.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
Did you ever go to the quack shack?
Were you ever, did you ever get sick or?
The what?
The quack shack, the hospital.
Oh, yeah, I busted my knee up.

on the track one time, I was trying to make a handoff to Bob Hall, we were practicing for the 880 relay, and Hall took off a little too soon, and I stretched too far to get the baton to it, and I hit that concrete curb, and just tore my knee up real bad, and Bill Dayton, the trainer, scrubbed it out with surgery,
Soap and put methionine on it.
And I got this big red streak coming up here.
And he said, you got to go to the hospital.
So I went over there to see Mom Claghorn.
And penicillin had just been invented.
So she said, roll over and pull up your gown.
And I did.
And she gave me a few shots of penicillin.
In three days, I was out of the hospital.
And describe her and her style of operating.

the hospital i didn't have that much direct contact with mom herself there was a cute little nurse there that who ministered to me and mom was she was sweet but firm no nonsense she was kind of like uh
A pleasant version of Marjorie Maine, I'd say.
And she was in charge.
There was no doubt that she was in charge.
Let's see.
You didn't go to Junction to summer camp or anything like that ever.
Every summer, even after you were married, did you go back and work in Beaumont?
Every summer, as soon as I could get out of here.
The nice thing about that,
These are distinguished student cards.
And I have one for every semester.
I was here at A&M.

And the nice thing about a distinguished student card was that if a prof says, OK, we're going to have a pop quiz, you could stand up and say, Dr. So-and-so, Professor So-and-so, I'm going to walk this class.
He'd say, all right.
And this is your get-out-of-jail-free card.
And the other nice thing about it was, if you were a distinguished student, you had no grade below a B in that course, you did not have to take a final exam.
You had to take a midterm, but not a final.
I never took a final.
And that was the
When I tell that to students season A's, golly, they can't believe that.
They never heard of that.
Did you make any grade that you then considered low, any course?
Yeah, I made a B in.
No C's and D's?
No.
Okay.
No, I never made a C. Okay.
And you didn't compute.
I was disappointed with a B that I got.
Nobody computed a GPA then.
You didn't know what your grade point average was, did you?
No.
You got a transcript, and it had on there the number of hours that you took and the number of grade points that you got.
And you could figure up your own grade point average if you wanted to.
But nobody talked about it in the way that they do today.
All right.
Evaluate the great, the best, the finest, the most respected teachers you had as you now think.
Talk about some of those.
Who were some of those fine teachers?
I wish I'd had some warning on that.
John B. Longley.
Johnny Longley.
What did he teach?
He taught life insurance.
He was the local American General Life Insurance Company representative here.
He was highly respected in the business community, and all of his students loved him.
Johnny was a World War II vet, and he'd gotten his foot shot off in Europe.
Another highly respected prof was Joe Vincent.
who taught property and casualty insurance.
These guys were private individuals who helped the school out because they had nobody with that kind of expertise.
Johnny had a degree, but it certainly wasn't an education.
And as you think about what they taught now, as you evaluated it, it was high quality, real world?
They told us what we needed to know about the subject matter at hand.
And when you went out into the real world, you found it worked.
It was exactly like they said it was.
Today, I can sit down and read a life insurance policy and a property and casualty insurance policy just as easily as I can read a novel based on what John B. Longley and Joe Vincent taught me.
And it hasn't changed.
And should identify for the person typing this up that Joe Vinson was one of the founders of what is now ANCO Insurance.
It was called Mitchell Vinson for a while.
Yes.
And then it became ANCO as they acquired ownership of an old company, Anderson.
And he's in cahoots with Red Cash.
Yes, yes, yes.
What about some other great teachers and or counselors that you know?
My, I'd have to say my Bulltex prof, a captain, he was an Air Force captain, and he encouraged me to apply for a regular commission.
I can't recall his name, but he kind of mentored me through Air Force Bulltex.
If you... And another was...
Ray Putnam, who taught agricultural economics.
And of course he was also assistant track coach.
And I had a course in ag eco that I took from him and was very impressed with his methodology.
Was there anybody that you would turn to for academic advice?
What should I take?
What courses should I attempt this year or next year?
Who was your counselor?
Didn't have any.
I'm not aware of any that we had in the business department because the curriculum was so narrow.
They had certain basic courses that you had to take.
And then there wasn't that much left over in the way of electives.
About how large was the average section of a business course?
How many students?
How many students?
I'd say 20 to 25 at the most.
And what was your routine?
Did you study just about every day, every night?
I took good notes.
I took shorthand in high school.
I would review those notes at night.
I would use the textbook if I knew that we were going to get questions coming out of it or if I needed to refer to the textbook to expand what we had gotten in class.
But what we got in class was practical stuff.
It was not theory.
It was hands on, here is a life insurance policy.
If you're going to be in insurance sales, well, these are the things you've got to know about this policy.
And here's how you make out a life insurance application.
You can study all the theory in Cushing Library.
It's not going to tell you how to fill out a life insurance application.
Now, by the time you were, say, a junior, what did you think your career was going to be?
What were you going to do, you hoped?
I was going to go with American General Life Insurance Company.
John B. had convinced me that that was the way I ought to go.
Headquartered in Houston.
Headquartered in Houston, headed up by Mr. Gus Wertham.
And John B. even arranged a visit for me with Mr. Gus in the spring of my senior year.
Although they already knew that
We were at the height of the Korean War, and they already knew that I'd been nominated for a regular commission, was gonna go that route.
But John B. wanted Mr. Gus to see me, and so that when I finished my tour of duty, that he said, there's a spot for you here at American General.
And I'm telling you, that was some sanctum sanctorum.
You had to get through two secretaries before you got into Mr. Gus's inner office.
Now, do you remember what building it was in Houston then?
It was in the Mel's Esperson building in downtown Houston.
Near the Rice Hotel.
Was he pleasant once you got in to chat with him?
Like talking to your grandfather.
Oh, how good, how good.
And did he offer you a...
a slot when you got out?
He said, there will be a place for you here when you finish your Air Force tour of duty.
He didn't mention salary or anything?
Oh, no.
You didn't talk about that.
I was going to say, that would have been, that would have been.
That would have been gauche.
Who were the campus, great campus personalities while you were here?
Now, the president when you got here was Gilchrist?
Or was it already, or was it?
Tom Harrington was the interim president.
And then he became, Gilchrist last year was I think the spring of 48, and then Tom Harrington was the interim.
And then he became the president I think in the spring semester of 49.
Did you guys see Dr. Harrington much, you students?
Dr. Harrington was always around the campus.
He walked.
He, you'd see him in the corridors.
I don't recall that he ever visited a class, but he knew your, he knew your name.
And I'd always see him walking back and forth on campus from one building to another.
Did your students have a high regard for him?
Absolutely the best.
What, who else was around, the notables?
Colonel Hayden L. Boatner.
Boatner was also visible.
Now, he was here when you got here?
Yes.
And he was the commandant?
He was.
Now, he was not an Aggie by background, was he?
He was a West Pointer.
Physically, he was what size?
Colonel Boatner was, I'd say, about 5'9", 5'10".
Slightly rotund.
Sparse hair.
Don't remember the color of his eyes.
but I remember he was all business.

I remember one time he smiled at me when I was sitting on the sidewalk outside of Guyon Hall talking to a friend of mine and Colonel Boatner comes walking up the sidewalk and I jumped up and I hit a brace and said good afternoon Colonel Boatner and he smiled.
He could actually smile.
And Colonel Joe Davis, who was a deputy commandant, and Joe Davis took over for Colonel Boatner.
Fighting Joe.
Fighting Joe, different kind of guy, accessible, reachable.
Boatner was distant.
And nobody would, y'all never thought about trying to play any jokes on him?
Oh yeah.
Oh really, on Boatner?
Oh yeah.
Such as?
WTAW, Watch Texas Aggies Win, they had a call-in request program for spinning records.
And at that time, Arthur Godfrey was very popular.
And he had a little ditty out called, Heat Big Smoke But No Fire.
And students would call it,
They'd get 10 requests a night for heat, big smoke, but no fire.
And I know it must have steamed Boatner, being a West Porter and all.
He was stuffy.
This is Cardinal Boatner speaking.
And everybody was supposed to face east and bow down.
Was Pinky around?
Pinky?
Yes, Pinky was around in his 36 green Ford Coupe.
You saw Pinky all over the campus, every place.
Now, were you all aware of whether or not he was an Aggie employee?
Yeah, we knew that he was the official greeter non-employee.
And he was just kept on, like old Uncle Mose was kept on the plantation.
And everybody made sure that Pinky was taken care of by
whatever means there was.
The deans during your era, who were they?
Well, Harrington was a dean.
He'd been promoted by the time I got here.
Dean John Paul Abbott, dean of arts and sciences.
I can't recall many of the deans outside my own school.
Then Reveille.
We had no Reveille here.
Where was Reveille?
The Reveille was dead.
No, but didn't they have a Reveille 2 or 3 or 4?
No.
You're saying there wasn't?
There was none.
Reveille 2 didn't come along until many years later in the 60s.
I didn't know that.
Go check the gravestones.
down there outside the... No, no, my astonishment, and I'm not questioning you, my astonishment is that I assumed that there had always been from Reveille 1 all the way through.
No, once Reveille 1 died, I don't know why there wasn't an immediate Reveille 2, but we had a dog that was kind of a favorite on campus, but never occupied the
the spot that Rivoli did.
Her name was Violet.
She was a black dog.
Matter of fact, I've got a picture here.
Yeah, that's Violet with some stray dog.
And the outstanding thing about Violet, she was an average-sized dog, but her paws were about as big as horses' hooves.
Monstrous.
And she was a friendly dog, and she'd wander through some decent people's dorms.
And we've met her here and all, but she was not a rebel.
Were you aware that there were secret fraternities on the campus then?
I was aware of one called the True Texans.
And I was aware of some people who were alleged
to have been true Texans, but none within my immediate sphere of influence.
Did you ever hear of the Stickers?
No.
Okay, let's go back to track now.
So sophomore year for you and track, did it go well?
It went very well.
We started out the year
with our usual dual and triangular meets.
And we went to the border Olympics.
And I won the high hurdles there and placed third in the low hurdles.
My lack of speed was starting to catch up with me.
I had technique and power, but I didn't have speed.
And the guys I was running against in the low hurdles
